<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910927-0068</DOCNO><DOCID>910927-0068.</DOCID><HL>   Bush Seeks Congress Action   On Sandamp;L Cleanup Structure</HL><DATE>09/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)EXECUTIVE (EXE)FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration has decided tolegislatively seek changes in the structure of thesavings-and-loan cleanup.   The administration is expected to send Congress today abill that would streamline the Resolution Trust Corp.,creating the position of chief executive officer to run theagency.</LP><TEXT>   The Treasury Department had previously argued againsthaving Congress make any changes in the cleanup's operation,saying it could make management changes without action byCongress.   The bill will also include the administration's requestfor an additional $80 million to fund the cleanup.   The pairing of these initiatives reflects a recognition bythe White House that Congress is unlikely to provide moremoney without changes in the structure of the RTC.   A House subcommittee is scheduled to begin action on thebill in early October.</TEXT></DOC>